@node copysign
@section @code{copysign}, @code{copysignf}---sign of @var{y}, magnitude of @var{x}
@findex copysign
@findex copysignf
@strong{Synopsis}
@example
#include <math.h>
double copysign (double @var{x}, double @var{y});
float copysignf (float @var{x}, float @var{y});

@end example
@strong{Description}@*
@code{copysign} constructs a number with the magnitude (absolute value)
of its first argument, @var{x}, and the sign of its second argument,
@var{y}.

@code{copysignf} does the same thing; the two functions differ only in
the type of their arguments and result.

@*
@strong{Returns}@*
@code{copysign} returns a @code{double} with the magnitude of
@var{x} and the sign of @var{y}.
@code{copysignf} returns a @code{float} with the magnitude of
@var{x} and the sign of @var{y}.

@*
@strong{Portability}@*
@code{copysign} is not required by either ANSI C or the System V Interface
Definition (Issue 2).


@*
